Modern Cuban society has had to struggle with a wide variety of behaviors that blatantly go against the traditional values of its culture, and which often result in tragic and violent acts. Fear and shame are the extreme consequences when people, especially women, find it difficult to express their feelings in the more open and often more aggressive environment prevailing today.

In addition, changing economic realities, political articles, social policies, and polygamy have all contributed to the recent increase in divorce and breakups between long-term partners.

Since relationships between husbands and wives are increasingly precarious, more and more men and women see their children as comfort and consolation.

Nowadays, in Cuba up to 54 percent of children of breakups or divorces live with their mothers who need dedicated community support and counseling while rearing their children.

Interestingly, American reporter Felecia Piggott gathered some responses from Cuban women while compiling her 2007 feature in Urban magazine entitled “What Men Want?” and found that many Cuban women were still counting on traditional roles in their marriages after six decades of communism. [5] As a matter of fact, the communist government vastly overlooked men’s role in the family until 2010, when Cuba’s Council of Ministers announced a national strategy to be “the best father.” [6]
